  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod5.id, title: "When HAZWOPER Medical Surveillance is Required", orderIndex: 0, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>When HAZWOPER Medical Surveillance is Required</h2><p>The Hazardous Waste Operations and Emergency Response (HAZWOPER) standard, codified at 29 CFR 1910.120, establishes medical surveillance requirements for workers involved in hazardous waste operations, treatment/storage/disposal (TSD) facility operations, and emergency response to hazardous substance releases. HAZWOPER medical surveillance is among the most comprehensive in OSHA regulation, reflecting the diverse and unpredictable nature of hazardous substance exposures these workers face.</p><h3>Four Triggers for HAZWOPER Medical Surveillance</h3><p>Medical surveillance under HAZWOPER is required for employees who meet any one of four triggers:</p><h4>Trigger 1: Exposed Above PELs for 30+ Days Per Year</h4><p>Employees who are or may be exposed to hazardous substances or health hazards at or above established permissible exposure limits (for any substance) for 30 or more days per year must receive medical surveillance. This trigger captures workers with chronic, ongoing exposures at hazardous waste sites or TSD facilities.</p><h4>Trigger 2: Required to Wear Respirator for 30+ Days Per Year</h4><p>Employees who wear a respirator for 30 or more days per year, regardless of the specific exposure level, are covered. This trigger recognizes that the act of wearing a respirator creates physiological stress that warrants medical monitoring, and that respirator-required work by definition involves potential hazardous substance exposure.</p><h4>Trigger 3: HAZMAT/Emergency Response Team Member</h4><p>Members of organized hazardous materials (HAZMAT) emergency response teams must receive medical surveillance regardless of the number of days of actual exposure or respirator use. Emergency responders face unpredictable exposures to unknown substances under high-stress conditions, making comprehensive baseline and ongoing medical surveillance essential.</p><h4>Trigger 4: Potential Overexposure or Illness Symptoms</h4><p>Any employee who develops signs or symptoms of possible overexposure to hazardous substances, or who is injured, becomes ill, or is exposed during an emergency response event, must receive medical surveillance. This trigger is event-driven and applies regardless of the employee's normal work activities.</p><h3>Types of HAZWOPER Workers</h3><p>HAZWOPER covers three distinct categories of workers, each with slightly different exposure profiles:</p><ul><li><strong>Hazardous waste site workers:</strong> Employees engaged in clean-up operations at uncontrolled hazardous waste sites (Superfund sites, brownfield remediation, underground storage tank removal). These workers face chronic exposure to soil and groundwater contaminants.</li><li><strong>TSD facility workers:</strong> Employees at permitted hazardous waste treatment, storage, and disposal facilities. These workers handle known hazardous wastes in controlled environments but face potential exposure through routine operations and emergency events.</li><li><strong>Emergency responders:</strong> Employees who respond to releases of hazardous substances — fire department HAZMAT teams, industrial emergency response teams, spill response contractors. These workers face acute, unpredictable exposures to unknown or multiple substances.</li></ul><h3>Levels of Protection</h3><p>HAZWOPER work involves four levels of personal protective equipment, each reflecting different exposure scenarios and requiring different medical evaluation considerations:</p><table><tr><th>Level</th><th>Protection</th><th>Typical Equipment</th><th>Medical Implications</th></tr><tr><td>Level A</td><td>Highest — vapor protection</td><td>Fully encapsulated suit + SCBA</td><td>Maximum physiological burden; highest medical clearance standard required</td></tr><tr><td>Level B</td><td>High — splash protection + respiratory</td><td>Chemical splash suit + SCBA or SAR</td><td>High physiological burden; SCBA medical evaluation required</td></tr><tr><td>Level C</td><td>Moderate — known contaminants</td><td>Chemical splash suit + APR</td><td>Moderate burden; standard respiratory evaluation</td></tr><tr><td>Level D</td><td>Basic — no respiratory hazard</td><td>Work clothes + safety glasses/gloves</td><td>Minimal burden; basic health assessment</td></tr></table><h3>Examination Frequency</h3><p>HAZWOPER specifies the following examination schedule:</p><ul><li><strong>Pre-placement:</strong> Before beginning hazardous waste work or joining an emergency response team</li><li><strong>Annual:</strong> At least every 12 months unless the physician determines a more frequent schedule is indicated</li><li><strong>Termination:</strong> Within 6 months of termination (if no exam within the prior 6 months). Note this is a longer window than the Asbestos Standard's 30-day requirement.</li><li><strong>As needed:</strong> Whenever the physician determines, based on examination findings or exposure events, that more frequent monitoring is warranted</li></ul><div class="case-study"><h4>Case Study: Multi-Trigger HAZWOPER Surveillance</h4><p>An environmental remediation company employed 25 field workers who performed both planned hazardous waste site cleanups and emergency spill response. The safety director needed to determine which employees required HAZWOPER medical surveillance. Analysis revealed: all 25 workers wore respirators more than 30 days per year (Trigger 2), 18 were exposed above PELs for at least one substance for 30+ days (Trigger 1), 8 were members of the company's emergency response team (Trigger 3), and during the past year, 3 workers had experienced acute exposure events requiring emergency decontamination (Trigger 4).</p><p>All 25 employees required HAZWOPER surveillance. The 8 emergency response team members required the most rigorous evaluation due to potential Level A/B work. The safety director established a comprehensive annual medical program with a single occupational health clinic, coordinating HAZWOPER, respiratory protection, and hearing conservation evaluations into a single annual examination to minimize worker downtime and examination costs.</p></div></div>` });

  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod5.id, title: "The HAZWOPER Physical: Comprehensive Testing Components", orderIndex: 1, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>The HAZWOPER Physical: Comprehensive Testing Components</h2><p>The HAZWOPER medical examination is the most robust occupational physical examination required by any OSHA standard. Because HAZWOPER workers may be exposed to a wide variety of chemical, biological, and physical hazards — often simultaneously and sometimes unpredictably — the medical examination must assess virtually every organ system that could be affected by hazardous substance exposure. The examining physician must have detailed knowledge of the specific hazards present at the employee's worksite to tailor the examination appropriately.</p><h3>Comprehensive Medical and Occupational History</h3><p>The history component of the HAZWOPER examination is extensive:</p><ul><li><strong>Detailed occupational exposure history:</strong> Current and prior employment involving hazardous substances, with specific attention to chemicals handled, duration of exposure, protection methods used, and any known overexposure events. This history may span decades and multiple employers.</li><li><strong>Chemical-specific exposure inventory:</strong> The physician should obtain a list of all hazardous substances present at the employee's current worksite and review the corresponding Safety Data Sheets (SDSs) to understand target organ effects, exposure limits, and biological monitoring markers.</li><li><strong>Personal protective equipment history:</strong> Types of PPE used, fit testing history, any problems experienced with PPE (skin reactions, breathing difficulty, heat stress events)</li><li><strong>Symptom review by organ system:</strong> Comprehensive review covering neurological (headaches, dizziness, memory problems, peripheral neuropathy), hepatic (abdominal pain, jaundice, fatigue), renal (urinary changes, edema), dermatologic (rashes, burns, sensitization), hematologic (bleeding, bruising, fatigue), and reproductive (fertility concerns, pregnancy outcomes) symptoms</li></ul><h3>Physical Examination: All Organ Systems</h3><p>The physical examination covers all organ systems with particular attention to those targeted by hazardous substances:</p><ul><li><strong>Neurological:</strong> Mental status, cranial nerves, motor and sensory function, deep tendon reflexes, coordination, gait. Solvents, heavy metals, and organophosphate pesticides can all cause neurological damage.</li><li><strong>Respiratory:</strong> Auscultation, assessment of respiratory effort, evaluation for signs of chronic lung disease</li><li><strong>Cardiovascular:</strong> Heart sounds, blood pressure, peripheral pulses, edema assessment</li><li><strong>Hepatic:</strong> Liver palpation, assessment for hepatomegaly, jaundice, spider angiomata — liver is a primary target for many industrial solvents and chemicals</li><li><strong>Dermatologic:</strong> Complete skin examination for chemical burns, contact dermatitis, sensitization reactions, suspicious lesions</li><li><strong>Musculoskeletal:</strong> Assessment of fitness for demanding physical work including PPE donning and doffing, confined space entry, and emergency response activities</li></ul><h3>Mandatory and Recommended Testing</h3><h4>Pulmonary Function Testing</h4><p>PFT is mandatory when the employee is required to wear a respirator (which is true for most HAZWOPER workers). Spirometry provides baseline and ongoing monitoring of lung function in a population chronically exposed to respiratory irritants and toxicants.</p><h4>Audiometry</h4><p>Hearing testing is included when the employee has noise exposure at or above 85 dBA (the OSHA action level under 29 CFR 1910.95). Many HAZWOPER work environments — heavy equipment operation at waste sites, pump operations, emergency response vehicle operations — generate hazardous noise levels.</p><h4>Laboratory Testing</h4><p>HAZWOPER laboratory testing is more extensive than for other OSHA medical surveillance programs:</p><ul><li><strong>Complete Blood Count (CBC) with differential:</strong> Screens for hematologic abnormalities — benzene-induced aplastic anemia, lead-induced anemia, toxic effects on white blood cell production</li><li><strong>Comprehensive Metabolic Panel:</strong> Liver function tests (AST, ALT, GGT, alkaline phosphatase, bilirubin) for solvent and chemical hepatotoxicity; kidney function tests (BUN, creatinine) for nephrotoxic chemical exposure; electrolytes for metabolic disturbances</li><li><strong>Heavy metals panel:</strong> Blood lead, blood mercury, urine cadmium, urine arsenic — baseline and monitoring for workers with potential heavy metal exposure. Lead is particularly common at hazardous waste sites and in demolition work involving lead paint.</li><li><strong>Urinalysis:</strong> Screens for kidney damage (proteinuria, hematuria), metabolic disease (glycosuria), and some chemical metabolites</li></ul><h4>Biological Monitoring</h4><p>For workers exposed to specific chemicals with established biological exposure indices (BEIs), the physician may order biological monitoring — measurement of the chemical or its metabolites in blood or urine. Examples: blood lead level for lead exposure, urine phenol for benzene exposure, cholinesterase levels for organophosphate pesticide exposure.</p><h4>Chest X-ray</h4><p>Chest radiography is at physician discretion for HAZWOPER (not mandatory as it is under the Asbestos Standard), but is commonly included for workers with respiratory irritant exposure, smokers, or workers with abnormal PFT findings.</p><h3>Physician Information Requirements</h3><p>The employer must provide the examining physician with:</p><ul><li>A description of the employee's duties and exposure</li><li>The employee's exposure levels or anticipated exposure levels</li><li>A description of personal protective equipment the employee uses or will use</li><li>Information from previous medical examinations not otherwise available to the physician</li></ul><div class="case-study"><h4>Case Study: HAZWOPER Physical Detecting Subclinical Toxicity</h4><p>A 42-year-old field supervisor for a hazardous waste remediation contractor had worked at various Superfund sites for 14 years. His annual HAZWOPER physical included the standard comprehensive laboratory panel. While his physical examination was unremarkable and he reported no symptoms, the laboratory results revealed: AST (liver enzyme) elevated at 68 U/L (normal <40), ALT elevated at 82 U/L (normal <41), GGT elevated at 95 U/L (normal <60). These values had been trending upward over the prior three annual examinations: AST: 42, 51, 68; ALT: 45, 58, 82; GGT: 48, 67, 95.</p><p>The occupational health physician recognized the pattern of progressive hepatic enzyme elevation and ordered follow-up testing: hepatitis B and C serology (negative), abdominal ultrasound (mild hepatic steatosis), and a detailed review of chemical exposures at recent work sites. The review revealed that the supervisor had spent 8 months at a site with significant trichloroethylene (TCE) groundwater contamination, performing daily groundwater sampling with Level C protection (half-mask APR).</p><p>TCE is a known hepatotoxicant. Biological monitoring revealed elevated trichloroacetic acid in urine (a TCE metabolite), confirming ongoing TCE absorption. The physician recommended: temporary removal from TCE-contaminated sites, repeat liver function testing monthly until normalization, modification of PPE requirements (upgrade to supplied-air respirator for future TCE site work), and no alcohol consumption during the monitoring period.</p><p>After 4 months of removal from TCE exposure, liver enzymes returned to normal. The employee returned to field work with enhanced PPE requirements for sites with chlorinated solvent contamination. The case demonstrated the value of longitudinal laboratory monitoring — without the trending data from three consecutive annual examinations, the gradual elevation might have been dismissed as a normal variant.</p></div></div>` });

  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod5.id, title: "HAZWOPER Respirator Requirements & SCBA Considerations", orderIndex: 2, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>HAZWOPER Respirator Requirements & SCBA Considerations</h2><p>HAZWOPER operations frequently require the highest levels of respiratory protection available — from half-mask air-purifying respirators at Level C to self-contained breathing apparatus (SCBA) at Levels A and B. The medical evaluation requirements for HAZWOPER respiratory protection must account for the extraordinary physiological demands placed on workers wearing SCBA and full encapsulation suits, often while performing strenuous physical work in extreme environmental conditions.</p><h3>HAZWOPER Protection Levels and Respirator Requirements</h3><h4>Level A: Maximum Respiratory and Skin Protection</h4><p>Level A protection is required when the hazard assessment indicates that the greatest possible level of skin, respiratory, and eye protection is needed. Typically specified for atmospheres with unidentified contaminants, known IDLH conditions involving skin-absorbable chemicals, or confined space entry with unknown atmospheric conditions. Equipment includes: fully encapsulating chemical-resistant suit (gas-tight), SCBA operated in pressure-demand mode, chemical-resistant inner and outer gloves, chemical-resistant steel-toe boots.</p><h4>Level B: Maximum Respiratory Protection with Splash Protection</h4><p>Level B is the highest level of respiratory protection with lesser skin protection. Specified when the contaminant is identified and requires the highest respiratory protection but vapor-tight skin protection is not required. Equipment includes: chemical splash suit (not gas-tight), SCBA or supplied-air respirator in pressure-demand mode, chemical-resistant inner and outer gloves, chemical-resistant steel-toe boots.</p><h3>SCBA Physiological Burden</h3><p>Self-contained breathing apparatus imposes extraordinary physiological demands that far exceed those of air-purifying respirators. Understanding these demands is critical for medical evaluation:</p><ul><li><strong>Weight:</strong> A complete SCBA assembly (cylinder, frame, harness, facepiece, regulator) weighs 25-35 pounds depending on the model and cylinder size. This weight is carried on the worker's back, increasing metabolic demand and placing stress on the spine, shoulders, and lower extremities.</li><li><strong>Air supply management:</strong> A standard 30-minute SCBA cylinder may provide only 15-20 minutes of actual use time during heavy physical work, as increased respiratory rate and tidal volume consume air more rapidly. Workers must monitor their air supply and manage egress time — a cognitive task performed under physical stress.</li><li><strong>Heat stress:</strong> The combination of SCBA, chemical-resistant suit, and physical work generates significant metabolic heat while the suit prevents evaporative cooling. Core body temperature can rise 1-2°F per 15 minutes of Level A/B work in moderate ambient temperatures. In hot environments, the rise can be even more rapid, approaching the heat stroke threshold of 104°F within 30 minutes.</li><li><strong>Cardiovascular demand:</strong> Studies have shown that working in full Level A/B ensemble at moderate intensity produces heart rates of 150-180 bpm — equivalent to vigorous running — even in workers performing tasks that would normally be classified as moderate physical work. This places SCBA work squarely in the "strenuous" cardiovascular demand category.</li><li><strong>Breathing resistance:</strong> While SCBA in pressure-demand mode provides positive pressure inside the facepiece (reducing inspiratory effort compared to negative-pressure respirators), the facepiece still creates some resistance, and the work of breathing against the regulator increases with respiratory rate.</li></ul><h3>Medical Evaluation for SCBA Users</h3><p>The medical evaluation for workers who will use SCBA must account for these extraordinary physiological demands. Beyond the standard respiratory medical evaluation under 1910.134, SCBA-qualified workers should be evaluated for:</p><ul><li><strong>Cardiovascular fitness:</strong> The PLHCP must assess whether the employee's cardiovascular system can handle sustained heart rates of 150+ bpm. This may require exercise stress testing (treadmill or cycle ergometer) for older workers or those with cardiovascular risk factors. A resting EKG may miss exercise-induced ischemia that would become apparent during SCBA work.</li><li><strong>Musculoskeletal fitness:</strong> The employee must be able to carry 25-35 pounds on their back while performing tasks including climbing ladders, crawling through confined spaces, carrying equipment, and potentially dragging or carrying victims. History of back injuries, knee problems, or shoulder injuries should be carefully evaluated.</li><li><strong>Thermoregulatory capacity:</strong> Employees with conditions that impair heat dissipation (obesity, cardiovascular disease, medications that impair sweating like anticholinergics) face elevated heat stroke risk during Level A/B work.</li><li><strong>Vision:</strong> Full-facepiece SCBA limits peripheral vision and may cause lens fogging. Employees with significant visual impairment may not be safe in IDLH environments where visual assessment of hazards is critical.</li></ul><h3>IDLH Conditions and Required Protection</h3><p>Immediately Dangerous to Life or Health (IDLH) atmospheres — oxygen-deficient (<19.5%), containing concentrations above IDLH values for specific chemicals, or containing unknown contaminants — require SCBA or equivalent protection. OSHA defines IDLH conditions as those that pose an immediate threat to life, would cause irreversible adverse health effects, or would impair an individual's ability to escape from a dangerous atmosphere.</p><p>In IDLH conditions, only pressure-demand SCBA or pressure-demand SAR with escape SCBA is acceptable. Air-purifying respirators of any type are prohibited in IDLH atmospheres because they cannot protect against oxygen deficiency or contaminant concentrations exceeding the APF.</p><div class="highlight-box warning-box"><h4>Emergency Response Fitness Standards</h4><p>Many fire departments and industrial emergency response teams adopt fitness standards that exceed OSHA minimums. The NFPA 1582 (Standard on Comprehensive Occupational Medical Program for Fire Departments) provides detailed medical fitness criteria including specific cardiovascular, pulmonary, neurological, and musculoskeletal standards for firefighters and emergency responders. While NFPA 1582 is not OSHA regulation, many employers adopt its criteria as best practice for their HAZMAT/emergency response teams.</p></div><div class="case-study"><h4>Case Study: SCBA Medical Evaluation Challenge</h4><p>A 50-year-old plant engineer at a chemical manufacturing facility was required to serve on the plant's emergency response team, which required SCBA use during chemical spill and fire response. His annual HAZWOPER physical revealed: BMI of 33 (obese), resting blood pressure 142/88, resting EKG showing occasional premature ventricular contractions (PVCs), and FEV1 at 82% predicted (borderline but technically passing).</p><p>The PLHCP was concerned about the cardiovascular risk profile and ordered a treadmill stress test. During the stress test, the employee achieved only 7 METs of exercise capacity (below the 10 MET target for heavy physical work) and developed frequent PVCs at peak exercise, though no ST-segment changes suggesting ischemia were observed.</p><p>The PLHCP's determination: cleared for air-purifying respirator use (half-mask and full-facepiece) in Level C and D protection; NOT cleared for SCBA use due to inadequate cardiovascular fitness for the physiological demands of Level A/B work. Recommendations included: participation in a structured exercise program with goal of improving cardiovascular fitness to 10+ METs, weight loss goal of 25 pounds, cardiology consultation for evaluation of PVCs, and re-evaluation in 6 months.</p><p>The plant reassigned the engineer to a support role on the emergency response team (incident command, not entry team) and recruited a replacement for the entry team from a younger, more physically fit pool of volunteers. After 8 months of structured exercise and 18 pounds of weight loss, the engineer achieved 10.5 METs on repeat stress testing with resolution of exercise-induced PVCs, and was cleared for SCBA use.</p></div></div>` });

  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod5.id, title: "Emergency Response Teams: Special Medical Requirements", orderIndex: 3, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Emergency Response Teams: Special Medical Requirements</h2><p>Emergency response teams — whether industrial HAZMAT teams, municipal fire department HAZMAT units, or contractor-based spill response teams — represent the most demanding application of occupational medical surveillance. These teams must be prepared to respond to chemical releases, fires, explosions, biological hazards, and radiological incidents with minimal notice, often in uncontrolled and evolving environments. The medical requirements for these teams go beyond standard HAZWOPER surveillance to include fitness-for-duty assessments, psychological readiness, and post-incident monitoring protocols.</p><h3>HAZMAT Team Medical Standards</h3><p>While OSHA's HAZWOPER standard establishes the regulatory floor for emergency response team medical surveillance, many organizations adopt enhanced medical standards that better reflect the extreme physical demands of emergency response work:</p><h4>Annual Physical Fitness Evaluations</h4><p>Beyond the standard HAZWOPER physical examination, many HAZMAT teams require annual fitness evaluations that include:</p><ul><li><strong>Cardiovascular endurance testing:</strong> Treadmill stress test or cycle ergometer test, with a target capacity of at least 10 METs (metabolic equivalents) — the approximate energy expenditure of heavy physical work in Level A/B PPE. Some teams use the Bruce Protocol (a graded treadmill test) with a target duration of at least 9 minutes (approximately 10 METs).</li><li><strong>Muscular strength and endurance:</strong> Assessment of grip strength (minimum 80 pounds for dominant hand), core strength, upper body strength (ability to perform donning/doffing tasks, equipment carrying, victim drag), and lower body strength (stair climbing with SCBA, ladder climbing).</li><li><strong>Flexibility and range of motion:</strong> HAZMAT response requires full range of motion in all major joints — particularly the shoulders (SCBA donning), knees (confined space entry), and spine (bending, lifting). Restricted range of motion can make PPE donning dangerous or impossible.</li><li><strong>Body composition:</strong> While OSHA does not establish a BMI limit for HAZMAT team members, many teams adopt guidelines recommending BMI below 30 (or body fat percentage targets) based on research showing increased heat stress risk, reduced exercise capacity, and impaired PPE fit in obese workers.</li></ul><h3>Heat Stress Management</h3><p>Heat-related illness is the most common acute medical problem affecting HAZMAT team members during response operations. Management strategies include:</p><ul><li><strong>Pre-hydration protocols:</strong> Team members should consume 16-32 ounces of water in the hour before donning Level A/B ensemble</li><li><strong>Work/rest cycles:</strong> Maximum work period in Level A/B protection is typically 20-30 minutes in moderate temperatures, with mandatory rest and active cooling between entries</li><li><strong>Core body temperature monitoring:</strong> Some teams use ingestible temperature pills (gastrointestinal temperature monitoring) during responses to track core temperature in real-time. A core temperature exceeding 101.3°F triggers mandatory rest and cooling; 103°F triggers medical evaluation.</li><li><strong>Active cooling during rehabilitation:</strong> Between work periods, team members should remove as much PPE as safely possible, move to shade or air-conditioned areas, consume cold fluids, and apply ice towels to neck, groin, and axillae</li></ul><h3>Rehabilitation Protocols</h3><p>HAZMAT response rehabilitation (rehab) is a structured medical monitoring process that occurs between work periods during extended operations:</p><ol><li><strong>Initial assessment:</strong> Upon exiting the hot zone, team members report to the rehab station for vital signs (heart rate, blood pressure, respiratory rate, temperature), hydration, and symptom assessment</li><li><strong>Rest period:</strong> Minimum 10-20 minutes of active rest with PPE removal, shade, and hydration</li><li><strong>Reassessment:</strong> Before re-entry, team members must meet clearance criteria: heart rate below 100 bpm, blood pressure within normal limits, core temperature below 100.5°F, no symptoms of heat illness, fatigue, or respiratory distress</li><li><strong>Mandatory medical evaluation trigger:</strong> Any team member who fails to meet reassessment criteria after 20 minutes of rest is prohibited from re-entry and must receive emergency medical evaluation</li></ol><h3>Critical Incident Stress Management</h3><p>HAZMAT response can expose team members to psychologically traumatic events — mass casualty incidents, child fatalities, grotesque injuries, and life-threatening personal exposure events. Critical Incident Stress Management (CISM) is an integrated system of crisis intervention services designed to mitigate the impact of traumatic stress:</p><ul><li><strong>Defusing:</strong> Brief (20-30 minute) group discussion immediately after a significant incident, facilitated by a trained peer supporter or mental health professional</li><li><strong>Critical Incident Stress Debriefing (CISD):</strong> Structured group process conducted 24-72 hours after a significant incident, led by a mental health professional and trained peers</li><li><strong>Individual counseling:</strong> Available to any team member who requests it or who is identified by peers, supervisors, or CISM team members as struggling with incident-related stress</li><li><strong>Follow-up:</strong> 30-day check-in with team members involved in significant incidents to assess for post-traumatic stress symptoms (intrusive memories, avoidance, hyperarousal, mood changes)</li></ul><h3>Post-Incident Medical Monitoring</h3><p>After any HAZMAT response involving actual or suspected chemical exposure, affected team members must receive post-incident medical monitoring:</p><ul><li><strong>Immediate decontamination assessment:</strong> Verify completeness of decontamination, check for chemical burns or skin absorption</li><li><strong>Acute symptom evaluation:</strong> Assess for respiratory irritation, eye injury, neurological symptoms (dizziness, confusion, headache), and dermal effects</li><li><strong>Documentation:</strong> Record all chemicals involved, duration of exposure, protection level used, decontamination procedures, and any symptoms experienced</li><li><strong>Follow-up testing:</strong> If specific chemicals are identified, appropriate biological monitoring should be performed within 24-48 hours (e.g., cholinesterase levels for organophosphate exposure, carboxyhemoglobin for carbon monoxide)</li><li><strong>Long-term monitoring:</strong> Some exposures (carcinogens, mutagens, reproductive toxicants) warrant long-term medical monitoring extending years beyond the exposure event</li></ul><div class="case-study"><h4>Case Study: HAZMAT Team Medical Program</h4><p>A major petrochemical complex maintained a 24-member emergency response team (ERT) organized into four 6-member platoons providing 24/7 coverage. The team responded to an average of 8 significant incidents per year plus 30+ smaller events. The medical program included:</p><p><strong>Annual medical program:</strong> Each team member received a comprehensive HAZWOPER physical including: medical/occupational history update, complete physical examination, spirometry, audiometry, exercise stress test (Bruce Protocol to 10+ METs), vision testing (near, far, color, peripheral), complete laboratory panel (CBC, CMP, heavy metals, urinalysis), psychological screening questionnaire, and SCBA-specific medical clearance.</p><p><strong>Fitness maintenance:</strong> Team members were required to maintain physical fitness year-round, with quarterly fitness assessments including: timed 1.5-mile run (under 12 minutes), 60-pound weighted stair climb (6 floors in under 3 minutes), equipment carry and drag (simulated victim rescue), and full PPE donning/doffing within time standards.</p><p><strong>Post-incident protocol:</strong> After every Level A or B response, all entry team members received: vital signs monitoring during rehab, symptom assessment at 2, 12, and 24 hours post-incident, targeted laboratory testing based on substances involved, CISM debriefing within 72 hours, and 30-day follow-up assessment.</p><p>Over a 10-year period, the program identified 3 team members who developed exercise-induced cardiac abnormalities warranting removal from entry team duty, 2 cases of occupational asthma linked to repeated chemical exposures during responses, and 1 case of PTSD following a mass casualty incident that was successfully treated with early intervention facilitated by the CISM program. The annual medical program cost was approximately $96,000 ($4,000 per team member), which management viewed as a modest investment relative to the $2.1 billion in facility assets the team protected.</p></div></div>` });

  // Module 5 Quiz Questions
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "Which of the following is NOT one of the four triggers for HAZWOPER medical surveillance?", options: ["Exposed above PELs for 30+ days/year", "Required to wear a respirator for 30+ days/year", "Working with hazardous substances in any capacity", "HAZMAT/Emergency Response Team member"], correctIndex: 2, explanation: "HAZWOPER surveillance is triggered by specific conditions: exposure above PELs 30+ days, respirator use 30+ days, HAZMAT team membership, or overexposure/illness. Simply working with hazardous substances doesn't automatically trigger surveillance.", orderIndex: 0 });
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "What is the approximate weight of a complete SCBA assembly?", options: ["5-10 pounds", "15-20 pounds", "25-35 pounds", "45-55 pounds"], correctIndex: 2, explanation: "A complete SCBA assembly (cylinder, frame, harness, facepiece, regulator) weighs 25-35 pounds, imposing significant physiological burden during emergency response work.", orderIndex: 1 });
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "Under HAZWOPER, the termination examination must be performed within what timeframe?", options: ["30 days of separation", "6 months of separation", "12 months of separation", "Not required"], correctIndex: 1, explanation: "HAZWOPER requires a termination examination within 6 months of leaving employment (if no exam within the prior 6 months). This is longer than the Asbestos Standard's 30-day window.", orderIndex: 2 });
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "Which PPE level requires the highest medical clearance standard?", options: ["Level D", "Level C", "Level B", "Level A"], correctIndex: 3, explanation: "Level A provides maximum protection with fully encapsulating suit and SCBA, imposing the greatest physiological burden. Medical clearance for Level A must account for heat stress, cardiovascular demand, and SCBA weight.", orderIndex: 3 });
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "What laboratory test would be most relevant for a HAZWOPER worker at a site contaminated with trichloroethylene (TCE)?", options: ["Blood lead level", "Liver function tests (AST, ALT, GGT)", "Cholinesterase levels", "Carboxyhemoglobin"], correctIndex: 1, explanation: "TCE is a known hepatotoxicant. Liver function tests monitor for TCE-induced liver damage. Blood lead tests for lead, cholinesterase for organophosphates, and carboxyhemoglobin for carbon monoxide.", orderIndex: 4 });
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "What minimum exercise capacity (in METs) is generally recommended for SCBA users performing heavy physical work?", options: ["5 METs", "7 METs", "10 METs", "15 METs"], correctIndex: 2, explanation: "A target of at least 10 METs (metabolic equivalents) is generally recommended for workers performing heavy physical work in Level A/B PPE with SCBA, reflecting the extreme cardiovascular demand of this work.", orderIndex: 5 });
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "During HAZMAT response rehabilitation, a team member's heart rate remains at 115 bpm after 20 minutes of rest. What action is required?", options: ["Allow re-entry if the team member feels ready", "Extend rest period by 10 minutes and reassess", "Prohibit re-entry and initiate emergency medical evaluation", "Allow re-entry with reduced work duration"], correctIndex: 2, explanation: "Team members who fail to meet reassessment criteria (heart rate below 100 bpm) after 20 minutes of rest are prohibited from re-entry and must receive emergency medical evaluation.", orderIndex: 6 });
  await storage.createQuizQuestion({ moduleId: mod5.id, question: "Which type of heavy metals panel would be most appropriate for HAZWOPER workers at a Superfund site?", options: ["Blood lead only", "Mercury only", "Lead, mercury, cadmium, and arsenic panel", "Iron and ferritin"], correctIndex: 2, explanation: "HAZWOPER workers at Superfund sites may be exposed to multiple heavy metals. A comprehensive panel including lead, mercury, cadmium, and arsenic provides baseline and monitoring for the most common contaminants found at hazardous waste sites.", orderIndex: 7 });

