  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod8.id, title: "OSHA Medical Surveillance Frequency Quick Reference", orderIndex: 0, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>OSHA Medical Surveillance Frequency Quick Reference</h2><p>This lesson provides consolidated reference tables for medical surveillance frequency requirements across the major OSHA standards. These tables are designed as quick-reference tools for safety directors, compliance managers, and occupational health professionals who need to quickly determine surveillance requirements for their workforce.</p><h3>Respiratory Protection Standard (29 CFR 1910.134)</h3><table><tr><th>Component</th><th>Initial</th><th>Ongoing</th><th>Notes</th></tr><tr><td>Medical Evaluation (Questionnaire)</td><td>Before first fit test or respirator use</td><td>When triggered (symptoms, condition change, work change)</td><td>NOT annually required unless triggered</td></tr><tr><td>PLHCP Clearance</td><td>Before first respirator use</td><td>Upon re-evaluation</td><td>Clearance types: full, with limitations, not cleared</td></tr><tr><td>Fit Testing</td><td>Before first respirator use</td><td>Annually + upon change in respirator or face</td><td>QLFT for APF ≤10; QNFT for APF >10</td></tr><tr><td>Training</td><td>Before first respirator use</td><td>Annually + when changes occur</td><td>Must include hands-on component</td></tr></table><h3>Asbestos Standard (29 CFR 1910.1001) — General Industry</h3><table><tr><th>Component</th><th>Initial</th><th>Ongoing</th><th>Notes</th></tr><tr><td>Medical Examination</td><td>Pre-placement (before or within 30 days of first exposure)</td><td>Annually</td><td>Comprehensive exam including history, physical, PFT</td></tr><tr><td>Spirometry (PFT)</td><td>At initial exam</td><td>At every annual exam (mandatory)</td><td>FVC and FEV1 minimum; ATS quality standards</td></tr><tr><td>Chest X-ray</td><td>At initial exam</td><td>See schedule below</td><td>Must be read by certified B-reader</td></tr><tr><td>Termination Exam</td><td>N/A</td><td>Within 30 days of separation</td><td>Not required if exam within last 12 months</td></tr></table><h4>Asbestos Chest X-ray Frequency Schedule</h4><table><tr><th>Years Since First Exposure</th><th>Age 15-35</th><th>Age 35-45</th><th>Age 45+</th></tr><tr><td>0-10 years</td><td>Every 5 years</td><td>Every 5 years</td><td>Every 5 years</td></tr><tr><td>10+ years</td><td>Every 5 years</td><td>Every 2 years</td><td>Annually</td></tr></table><h3>HAZWOPER Standard (29 CFR 1910.120)</h3><table><tr><th>Component</th><th>Initial</th><th>Ongoing</th><th>Notes</th></tr><tr><td>Medical Examination</td><td>Pre-placement</td><td>Annually (at minimum)</td><td>Most comprehensive occupational physical</td></tr><tr><td>Spirometry</td><td>At initial exam (if respirator required)</td><td>Annually (if respirator required)</td><td>Required when employee wears respirator</td></tr><tr><td>Audiometry</td><td>At initial exam (if noise exposed)</td><td>Annually (if noise exposed)</td><td>When exposed ≥85 dBA TWA</td></tr><tr><td>Laboratory Testing</td><td>At initial exam</td><td>Annually</td><td>CBC, CMP, heavy metals as indicated by exposure</td></tr><tr><td>Chest X-ray</td><td>Physician discretion</td><td>Physician discretion</td><td>Not mandatory — unlike Asbestos Standard</td></tr><tr><td>Termination Exam</td><td>N/A</td><td>Within 6 months of separation</td><td>Not required if exam within last 6 months</td></tr></table><h3>Hearing Conservation Standard (29 CFR 1910.95)</h3><table><tr><th>Component</th><th>Initial</th><th>Ongoing</th><th>Notes</th></tr><tr><td>Baseline Audiogram</td><td>Within 6 months of first exposure (or 12 months with interim HPD use)</td><td>N/A</td><td>14-hour noise-free period required before baseline</td></tr><tr><td>Annual Audiogram</td><td>N/A</td><td>Annually</td><td>Compared to baseline for STS detection</td></tr><tr><td>STS Notification</td><td>N/A</td><td>Within 21 days of determination</td><td>Written notification to employee</td></tr></table><h3>Side-by-Side Comparison: The Three Major Standards</h3><table><tr><th>Feature</th><th>Respiratory (1910.134)</th><th>Asbestos (1910.1001)</th><th>HAZWOPER (1910.120)</th></tr><tr><td>Annual Exam Required?</td><td>No (trigger-based)</td><td>Yes (mandatory)</td><td>Yes (mandatory)</td></tr><tr><td>PFT Required?</td><td>PLHCP discretion</td><td>Mandatory annually</td><td>If respirator required</td></tr><tr><td>Chest X-ray?</td><td>PLHCP discretion</td><td>Mandatory on schedule</td><td>Physician discretion</td></tr><tr><td>B-Reader Required?</td><td>No</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr><tr><td>Lab Testing?</td><td>PLHCP discretion</td><td>Not specified</td><td>Yes (extensive)</td></tr><tr><td>Termination Exam?</td><td>Not required</td><td>Within 30 days</td><td>Within 6 months</td></tr><tr><td>Record Retention</td><td>Duration + 30 years*</td><td>Duration + 30 years</td><td>Duration + 30 years</td></tr></table><p>*Via 29 CFR 1910.1020</p><h3>Quick-Reference Decision Tree: Which Standard Applies?</h3><div class="highlight-box"><h4>Step 1: Does the employee wear a respirator?</h4><p>If YES → 29 CFR 1910.134 (Respiratory Protection) applies</p><h4>Step 2: Is the employee exposed to asbestos at or above the PEL (0.1 f/cc) or EL (1.0 f/cc)?</h4><p>If YES → 29 CFR 1910.1001 (Asbestos) applies IN ADDITION to 1910.134</p><h4>Step 3: Is the employee engaged in hazardous waste operations, TSD facility operations, or emergency response?</h4><p>If YES → 29 CFR 1910.120 (HAZWOPER) applies IN ADDITION to 1910.134</p><h4>Step 4: Is the employee exposed to noise at or above 85 dBA TWA?</h4><p>If YES → 29 CFR 1910.95 (Hearing Conservation) applies</p><p>Note: Multiple standards can apply simultaneously to a single employee. All applicable requirements must be met.</p></div></div>` });

  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod8.id, title: "Official OSHA Forms, Standards & Resources", orderIndex: 1, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Official OSHA Forms, Standards & Resources</h2><p>This lesson provides a comprehensive reference guide to the OSHA standards, forms, and resources that underpin medical surveillance programs. Safety professionals should maintain familiarity with these resources and know where to access them when questions arise.</p><h3>Primary OSHA Standards</h3><h4>29 CFR 1910.134 — Respiratory Protection</h4><p>The comprehensive standard governing all aspects of respiratory protection in general industry. Key appendices include: Appendix A — Fit Testing Procedures (mandatory), Appendix B-1 — User Seal Check Procedures (mandatory), Appendix B-2 — Respirator Cleaning Procedures (mandatory), Appendix C — OSHA Respirator Medical Evaluation Questionnaire (mandatory), and Appendix D — Information for Employees Using Respirators When Not Required (mandatory for voluntary use).</p><h4>29 CFR 1910.1001 — Asbestos (General Industry)</h4><p>Covers asbestos exposure in general industry workplaces including manufacturing, building maintenance, and custodial operations in buildings containing ACM. Includes detailed medical surveillance requirements, exposure monitoring, employee notification, and record keeping provisions.</p><h4>29 CFR 1926.1101 — Asbestos (Construction)</h4><p>The construction counterpart to 1910.1001, covering asbestos exposure during demolition, renovation, abatement, and construction activities. Shares the same PEL and medical surveillance framework but includes construction-specific provisions for competent person requirements, work classifications (Class I through IV), and negative exposure assessments.</p><h4>29 CFR 1910.120 — HAZWOPER</h4><p>The comprehensive standard for hazardous waste operations and emergency response, covering site workers, TSD facility workers, and emergency responders. Addresses training levels (40-hour, 24-hour, 8-hour refresher), site characterization, health and safety planning, medical surveillance, and emergency response procedures.</p><h4>29 CFR 1910.95 — Occupational Noise Exposure (Hearing Conservation)</h4><p>Establishes requirements for hearing conservation programs including noise monitoring, audiometric testing, hearing protection, and training when employee noise exposure equals or exceeds an 8-hour TWA of 85 dBA.</p><h4>29 CFR 1910.1020 — Access to Employee Exposure and Medical Records</h4><p>Establishes requirements for the preservation and access to employee exposure and medical records. Applies to all employers who make, maintain, contract for, or have access to employee medical or exposure records. Mandates duration of employment plus 30 years retention for medical records and 30 years for exposure records.</p><h3>Key OSHA Resources</h3><ul><li><strong>OSHA.gov:</strong> The official OSHA website provides full text of all standards, interpretation letters, compliance directives, and educational materials. The Standards page allows direct access to any CFR section. Interpretation letters are particularly valuable as they provide OSHA's official position on specific compliance questions.</li><li><strong>OSHA Small Entity Compliance Guides:</strong> Available for respiratory protection and several substance-specific standards. These guides translate regulatory language into practical, step-by-step compliance instructions tailored for small businesses.</li><li><strong>OSHA On-Site Consultation Program:</strong> Free, confidential consultation service available in every state, funded by OSHA but administered by state agencies. Consultants help small businesses identify hazards and build compliance programs without citations or penalties. Available at www.osha.gov/consultation.</li><li><strong>OSHA Training Institute (OTI) Education Centers:</strong> Located across the country, OTI Education Centers offer courses on OSHA standards including respiratory protection, asbestos, HAZWOPER, and hearing conservation. Many courses qualify for continuing education credits.</li></ul><h3>NIOSH Resources</h3><ul><li><strong>NIOSH Pocket Guide to Chemical Hazards:</strong> Essential reference providing PELs, RELs, IDLH values, and exposure routes for hundreds of chemical substances. Available online and as a free mobile app.</li><li><strong>NIOSH Spirometry Training Program:</strong> Provides training and certification for spirometry technicians conducting occupational PFTs. Certified technicians ensure test quality that withstands regulatory scrutiny.</li><li><strong>B-Reader Certification Program:</strong> NIOSH administers the B-Reader certification for physicians interpreting chest radiographs for pneumoconiosis. The program maintains a current list of certified B-readers searchable by location.</li><li><strong>NIOSH Respirator Decision Logic:</strong> A systematic framework for selecting appropriate respiratory protection based on hazard type, concentration, and workplace conditions.</li></ul><h3>American Thoracic Society (ATS) Resources</h3><ul><li><strong>ATS/ERS Spirometry Standardization:</strong> The definitive technical standard for performing and interpreting spirometry, referenced by OSHA for PFT quality criteria.</li><li><strong>ATS Occupational Lung Disease Guidelines:</strong> Clinical practice guidelines for diagnosing and managing occupational lung diseases including asbestosis, silicosis, and occupational asthma.</li></ul><h3>Professional Organizations</h3><ul><li><strong>American College of Occupational and Environmental Medicine (ACOEM):</strong> Provides practice guidelines, position statements, and continuing education for occupational medicine physicians. Their guidelines on medical surveillance are widely referenced by PLHCPs.</li><li><strong>American Industrial Hygiene Association (AIHA):</strong> Resources for industrial hygienists conducting exposure assessments, including technical guides for asbestos, noise, and chemical exposure monitoring.</li><li><strong>National Safety Council (NSC):</strong> Educational resources, training programs, and safety data for occupational health and safety professionals.</li></ul><div class="highlight-box"><h4>Building Your Reference Library</h4><p>Every safety professional managing a medical surveillance program should maintain ready access to: the full text of applicable OSHA standards (available free at osha.gov), the NIOSH Pocket Guide to Chemical Hazards (free online and app), current OSHA penalty structure (updated annually for inflation), a list of certified B-readers in your region (NIOSH website), and your state's OSHA Consultation Program contact information.</p></div></div>` });

  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod8.id, title: "Course Summary & Implementation Roadmap", orderIndex: 2, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Course Summary & Implementation Roadmap</h2><p>Over the preceding seven modules, we have covered the full spectrum of OSHA medical surveillance requirements — from the foundational Respiratory Protection Standard through asbestos and HAZWOPER surveillance, fit testing, pulmonary function testing, employer compliance programs, and advanced topics. This lesson synthesizes the key takeaways from each module and provides a practical implementation roadmap for employers building or improving their medical surveillance programs.</p><h3>Module-by-Module Key Takeaways</h3><h4>Module 1: Respiratory Protection Foundation</h4><ul><li>Medical evaluation must precede fit testing and respirator use — no exceptions</li><li>The PLHCP receives work condition information from the employer and provides only a fit/not-fit determination — no diagnoses</li><li>Any positive response on Part A of the questionnaire triggers mandatory follow-up examination</li><li>Re-evaluation is trigger-based, not annual (key distinction from other standards)</li></ul><h4>Module 2: Fit Testing</h4><ul><li>Annual fit testing is mandatory for all tight-fitting respirators</li><li>QLFT for APF ≤10 (half-masks, N95s); QNFT required for APF >10 (full-facepiece)</li><li>Minimum Fit Factors: 100 for half-mask, 500 for full-facepiece</li><li>Clean-shaven requirement is absolute in the facepiece seal area</li></ul><h4>Module 3: Pulmonary Function Testing</h4><ul><li>The 80% Rule: FEV1 ≥80% predicted, FVC ≥80% predicted, FEV1/FVC ≥70%</li><li>Obstructive pattern (low FEV1, low ratio) suggests asthma/COPD</li><li>Restrictive pattern (low FVC, normal ratio) suggests fibrosis/asbestosis</li><li>15% decline from personal baseline triggers mandatory investigation</li></ul><h4>Module 4: Asbestos Surveillance</h4><ul><li>PEL: 0.1 f/cc TWA; Excursion Limit: 1.0 f/cc over 30 minutes</li><li>Annual examination is mandatory (not trigger-based)</li><li>PFT is mandatory at every examination</li><li>Chest X-rays follow age/exposure-based schedule and require B-reader interpretation</li><li>Records retained for duration of employment + 30 years</li></ul><h4>Module 5: HAZWOPER Surveillance</h4><ul><li>Four triggers: exposure above PELs 30+ days, respirator use 30+ days, HAZMAT team membership, or overexposure/illness</li><li>Most comprehensive occupational physical (all organ systems, extensive labs)</li><li>SCBA users need cardiovascular fitness assessment (10+ METs target)</li><li>Termination exam within 6 months of separation</li></ul><h4>Module 6: Compliance Programs</h4><ul><li>Written RPP must be worksite-specific with all mandatory elements</li><li>1910.134 consistently ranks in OSHA's top 10 most-cited standards</li><li>Maximum penalties: $16,131 per Serious, $161,323 per Willful/Repeat</li><li>Record retention: duration of employment + 30 years for all medical records</li></ul><h4>Module 7: Advanced Topics</h4><ul><li>Multi-hazard workers benefit from integrated annual examinations</li><li>Aging workers require enhanced cardiovascular and pulmonary assessment</li><li>Hearing conservation integrates with respiratory protection programs</li><li>The cost of compliance is always less than the cost of non-compliance</li></ul><h3>30/60/90 Day Implementation Plan</h3><div class="highlight-box"><h4>Days 1-30: Foundation</h4><ul><li>Conduct hazard assessment to identify all employees requiring medical surveillance</li><li>Select and contract with a qualified PLHCP/occupational health clinic</li><li>Develop written RPP with worksite-specific procedures</li><li>Distribute OSHA medical questionnaires to all identified employees</li><li>Establish employee tracking database</li></ul><h4>Days 31-60: Medical Evaluations and Clearance</h4><ul><li>Complete PLHCP review of all questionnaires</li><li>Schedule and complete follow-up examinations for employees with positive responses</li><li>Obtain PLHCP written recommendations for all employees</li><li>Identify any employees requiring limitations or alternative respiratory protection</li><li>Procure respirators (multiple sizes and models) based on hazard assessment</li></ul><h4>Days 61-90: Fit Testing, Training, and Launch</h4><ul><li>Conduct fit testing for all medically cleared employees</li><li>Deliver comprehensive respirator training (classroom plus hands-on)</li><li>Finalize documentation for all program elements</li><li>Conduct initial program audit to verify completeness</li><li>Establish ongoing monitoring systems (fit test tracking, re-evaluation triggers, surveillance calendars)</li></ul></div><h3>KPIs for Program Effectiveness</h3><table><tr><th>KPI</th><th>Target</th><th>Measurement Frequency</th></tr><tr><td>Medical evaluation currency rate</td><td>100%</td><td>Monthly</td></tr><tr><td>Fit test currency rate</td><td>≥98%</td><td>Monthly</td></tr><tr><td>Training completion rate</td><td>100%</td><td>Quarterly</td></tr><tr><td>PFT quality rate (ATS criteria met)</td><td>≥90%</td><td>Annually</td></tr><tr><td>Symptom report response time</td><td>&lt;48 hours to PLHCP referral</td><td>Per occurrence</td></tr><tr><td>OSHA citations</td><td>Zero</td><td>Annually</td></tr></table><h3>ROI of Compliance vs. Cost of Violations</h3><p>For a typical employer with 50 respirator users, the annual cost of a fully compliant respiratory protection and medical surveillance program is approximately $15,000-$25,000 (medical evaluations, fit testing, training, program administration, equipment). This represents the cost of one to two Serious citations — before considering the additional costs of OSHA penalties for multiple violations, operational disruption during abatement, increased insurance premiums, potential workers' compensation claims, and reputational damage.</p><p>The arithmetic is unambiguous: compliance is cheaper than non-compliance, every time.</p><h3>Next Steps: CCH Free Consultation</h3><p>If you are building a new medical surveillance program, enhancing an existing program, or need guidance on any aspect of OSHA respiratory protection, asbestos, or HAZWOPER compliance, CCH offers a free initial consultation with our occupational health and safety experts. Our team includes certified industrial hygienists, safety professionals, and occupational health consultants with decades of experience helping employers of all sizes achieve and maintain regulatory compliance. Contact us at info@caboreconsulting.com to schedule your consultation.</p></div>` });

  await storage.createLesson({ moduleId: mod8.id, title: "Comprehensive Final Examination Preparation", orderIndex: 3, content: `<div class="lesson-content"><h2>Comprehensive Final Examination Preparation</h2><p>This study guide covers the major regulatory citations, key numerical thresholds, and common scenarios you will encounter on the comprehensive final examination. Review each section carefully and refer back to the detailed lessons for any topics where you need additional reinforcement.</p><h3>Critical Regulatory Citations to Know</h3><table><tr><th>Citation</th><th>Standard</th><th>Key Requirement</th></tr><tr><td>1910.134(e)</td><td>Respiratory Protection</td><td>Medical evaluation before fit test or respirator use</td></tr><tr><td>1910.134(e)(5)</td><td>Respiratory Protection</td><td>Employer information to PLHCP (respirator type, duration, conditions)</td></tr><tr><td>1910.134(e)(6)</td><td>Respiratory Protection</td><td>PLHCP written recommendation content (fit/not fit only)</td></tr><tr><td>1910.134(e)(7)</td><td>Respiratory Protection</td><td>Re-evaluation triggers (symptoms, condition changes, work changes)</td></tr><tr><td>1910.134(f)</td><td>Respiratory Protection</td><td>Fit testing requirements (initial, annual, upon change)</td></tr><tr><td>1910.134(c)</td><td>Respiratory Protection</td><td>Written RPP with worksite-specific procedures</td></tr><tr><td>1910.1001(l)</td><td>Asbestos</td><td>Medical surveillance requirements</td></tr><tr><td>1910.1001(l)(3)</td><td>Asbestos</td><td>Chest X-ray frequency schedule</td></tr><tr><td>1910.120(f)</td><td>HAZWOPER</td><td>Medical surveillance requirements</td></tr><tr><td>1910.95(g)</td><td>Hearing Conservation</td><td>Audiometric testing program</td></tr><tr><td>1910.1020</td><td>Access to Records</td><td>Record retention (employment + 30 years)</td></tr></table><h3>Key Numerical Thresholds</h3><table><tr><th>Value</th><th>Significance</th></tr><tr><td>0.1 f/cc (8-hr TWA)</td><td>Asbestos PEL — triggers medical surveillance</td></tr><tr><td>1.0 f/cc (30 min)</td><td>Asbestos Excursion Limit</td></tr><tr><td>0.05 f/cc</td><td>Asbestos Action Level — triggers exposure monitoring</td></tr><tr><td>85 dBA TWA</td><td>Noise Action Level — triggers hearing conservation</td></tr><tr><td>APF 10</td><td>Half-mask, N95 protection factor</td></tr><tr><td>APF 50</td><td>Full-facepiece protection factor</td></tr><tr><td>FF 100</td><td>Minimum Fit Factor for half-mask (QNFT)</td></tr><tr><td>FF 500</td><td>Minimum Fit Factor for full-facepiece (QNFT)</td></tr><tr><td>FEV1 ≥80% predicted</td><td>PFT passing threshold (occupational guideline)</td></tr><tr><td>FVC ≥80% predicted</td><td>PFT passing threshold (occupational guideline)</td></tr><tr><td>FEV1/FVC ≥70%</td><td>Normal ratio threshold</td></tr><tr><td>15% decline from baseline</td><td>Significant PFT decline triggering investigation</td></tr><tr><td>25-30 mL/year</td><td>Normal FEV1 decline rate (non-smokers)</td></tr><tr><td>10 dB average shift</td><td>Standard Threshold Shift (hearing)</td></tr><tr><td>$16,131</td><td>Maximum penalty per Serious violation (2024)</td></tr><tr><td>$161,323</td><td>Maximum penalty per Willful/Repeat violation (2024)</td></tr><tr><td>15 working days</td><td>Contest period for OSHA citations</td></tr><tr><td>Employment + 30 years</td><td>Medical record retention period</td></tr></table><h3>Common Exam Scenarios</h3><h4>Scenario Type 1: Medical Evaluation Timing</h4><p>"A new hire is scheduled to start work in a respirator-required area on Monday. Their medical questionnaire was submitted to the PLHCP on Friday. The PLHCP has not yet reviewed it. Can the employee begin work?" Answer: No. Medical clearance must precede both fit testing and respirator use. The employee cannot work in a respirator-required area until the PLHCP issues a clearance determination.</p><h4>Scenario Type 2: Fit Test Validity</h4><p>"An employee passed a fit test on a 3M 6200 half-mask 8 months ago. The company switches to a MSA Advantage 200LS. Can the employee use the new respirator?" Answer: No. The employee must be fit tested on the new MSA respirator before using it. Fit tests are specific to make, model, style, and size.</p><h4>Scenario Type 3: PFT Interpretation</h4><p>"An employee's PFT shows FEV1 at 72% predicted and FVC at 90% predicted. What is the pattern?" Answer: Obstructive pattern — FEV1 is reduced below 80% while FVC is preserved, producing a low FEV1/FVC ratio (72/90 = 80% — borderline). This pattern suggests asthma or COPD.</p><h4>Scenario Type 4: Asbestos X-ray Scheduling</h4><p>"A 42-year-old worker has been exposed to asbestos for 12 years. How often should chest X-rays be performed?" Answer: Every 2 years. The worker is in the 10+ years exposure category and age 35-45 category, which requires biennial X-rays per the asbestos standard's frequency schedule.</p><h4>Scenario Type 5: Record Retention</h4><p>"An employee worked at a company for 15 years with asbestos exposure. The employee resigned 5 years ago. Can the company destroy the employee's medical records?" Answer: No. Records must be retained for duration of employment (15 years) plus 30 years = 45 years from date of creation. Only 20 years have passed (15 working + 5 since departure). Records must be maintained for another 25 years.</p><h4>Scenario Type 6: PLHCP Confidentiality</h4><p>"The PLHCP's written recommendation to the employer states: 'Employee is cleared for half-mask use. Employee has well-controlled Type 2 diabetes.' Is this appropriate?" Answer: No. The PLHCP's written recommendation to the employer should not contain specific diagnoses. The diabetes information is confidential medical information that should not be disclosed to the employer.</p><div class="highlight-box"><h4>Final Exam Preparation Tips</h4><ul><li>Focus on understanding the differences between the three major standards (Respiratory Protection, Asbestos, HAZWOPER) — especially which components are mandatory vs. discretionary under each</li><li>Know the numerical thresholds cold — PEL values, Fit Factors, PFT criteria, penalty amounts</li><li>Understand the information flow — what goes to the employer vs. what stays confidential</li><li>Practice scenario-based reasoning — most exam questions present a workplace situation requiring application of regulatory knowledge</li><li>Remember the overarching principle: the purpose of medical surveillance is to protect worker health, not to create paperwork</li></ul></div></div>` });

